@node intro "Introduction"

  @{b}Introduction@{ub}

  MainPrefs is a program to configure your system under AmigaOS; you can

  - start preference programs and edit config files,
  - view and change assigns, and
  - view and change environment variables.

  So MainPrefs is an easy to use platform that ist not included in AmigaOS.

  @{b}Changing important environment variables may lead to unpredictable
  results. You should also be cautious when editing the file
  "s:startup-sequence".@{ub} Change only the preferences you really know!
@endnode

@node require "Requirements and Compatibility"

  @{b}Requirements and Compatibility@{ub}

  You need at least Amiga OS 3.5.

  Older versions are not supported as the implementation is based on
  Reaction and recent library versions.

  MainPrefs is compatible with HappyENV.


  see also
  @{" Support " link team}
@endnode

@node install "Installation"

  @{b}Installation and deinstallation@{ub}

  The install script @{i}MainPrefs.install @{ui} installs all the required
  files.

  If you have already installed an old version of MainPrefs, you can decide
  to keep your preference file which will be converted to the new format the
  next time MainPrefs starts.

  As alternative, you can copy the MainPrefs directory to some place on your
  harddisk; then replace the file @{i}MainPrefs.guide @{ui} by the
  documentation in your language, e.g. @{i}docs/MainPrefsE.guide @{ui}.

  To deinstall the program just delete the program directory.


  see also
  @{" Support " link team}
@endnode

@node use "Usage"

  @{b}Usage@{ub}

  Workbench start:

    To start the program double-click on the icon @{i}MainPrefs @{ui}.
    You can change the following Tooltypes:

    - X, Y, WIDTH, HEIGHT (optional)
      enter the position and size of the MainPrefs window

    - HELPFILE  (optional)
      enter the complete filename of the MainPrefs documentation
      (mainprefs.guide)

    - PREFFILE  (optional)
      enter the complete filename of the MainPrefs preference file
      (mainprefs.prefs)

  Shell start:

    mainprefs
    or
    run <>NIL: mainprefs

    Arguments are not supported.


  The appearing window offers four possibilities:

   @{" System:    Run programs and edit files " link prog}
   @{" Assigns:   View and change assigns     " link assigns}
   @{" Variables: View and change variables   " link variables}
   @{" Settings:  Configure MainPrefs         " link config}

  The menu consists of the topics

   @{" Help                        " link help}
   @{" Save Preferences            " link prefs}
   @{" About                       " link info}
   @{" Iconify                     " link iconify}
   @{" Quit                        " link quit}

  For a description of standard window buttons please refer to the AmigaOS
  manuals.

@endnode

@node prog "System"

  @{b}System@{ub}

  You can add standard system preference programs or little tools like
  Intellifont in this List. They can be started via Workbench, ARexx or CLI.
  Files like the known startup files @{i}s:startup-sequence @{ui} and @{i}s:user-startup @{ui}
  can be inserted here to change them fast and easy (type "Edit").
  But you can also add any textfile used to specify properties of a part of
  your system.
  It is also possible to insert a directory (e.g. "WBStartup"). When you
  specify "WB" type, you will get a workbench window with the contents of
  this drawer when you double-click on it.

  The list consists of groups that contain file entries. You can open and
  close the group by means of the arrow at the left.
  Start a program by a double-click on its name.
  Create a new entry by clicking on @{i}New @{ui}, remove the highlighted
  entry by clicking @{i}Remove @{ui}.
  Sort the entries with the @{i}up and down @{ui} arrows.


   @{b}New@{ub}

   To add a file to the list you first have to create a new entry. Then you
   can change the properties of this entry.

   You can enter the name in the left field and the complete filename in
   the right field.
   Alternatively you can click on the icon in the middle and search for the
   file in the appearing file requester.
   With the button on the right side you can choose what MainPrefs will do
   when you double-click on the entry:

    WB:    start as if you would double-click on the files icon
    AREXX: start as an ARexx-Skript
    CLI:   start as CLI-command
    Edit:  edit this file with the given @{" editor " link editor}
    Group: this entry is only a title for a group of files, a double-click
           will have no effect

   You can also switch between types.
   If you enter a new name, filename or select an other type, the entry is
   immediately changed.

   An easy way to add entries is to drop icons in the MainPrefs window, each
   dropped file will be inserted as "WB" started, what can be changed of
   course by clicking the entry and choosing the new type.

   @{b}up and down @{ub}

   When you have inserted a new entry (or want to change the order) you can
   move the current entry with the two arrows in the middle.
   If it is a file, it will be moved inside its group or into the next one;
   the members of the next group will be shown if necessary.
   If it is a group, the whole group is moved.

   @{b}Remove@{ub}

   If an entry in the list is selected, clicking on the @{i}Remove @{ui}-Button
   will remove this entry from the list. If it is a group and has at least one
   member, you will be asked if you will remove the whole group.

   Of course the file is not deleted from disk.


  To save changes to the list, choose the menu item @{" Save preferences " link prefs}.


  see also
  @{" Editor           " link editor}.
  @{" Save preferences " link prefs}
@endnode

@node assigns "Assigns"

  @{b}Assigns@{ub}

  With AmigaOS it is possible to create logical devices, what makes the use of
  volumes and directories easy and efficient.

  In the shown list all defined logical devices can be seen, the last column
  showing the special type of the device (look below).
  A double-click on an entry will show a Workbench window with the contents of
  this drawer.
  Add another assign by clicking on @{i}Add @{ui}, remove the highlighted
  assign by clicking @{i}Remove @{ui} (of cource the directory is not deleted
  from harddisk!). With @{i}Sort by @{ui} you can change the order of the
  list, and with @{i}Reload @{ui} you can update the list of assigns.


   @{b}Add@{ub}

   To add a logical device you have to enter the name in the left field and
   the path of the directory to be assigned in the right field. Alternatively
   you can click on the icon in the middle and search for the directory in the
   appearing file requester, or simply drop the icon of a directory in
   MainPrefs window.
   The assign type can be specified with the button at the right side:

   normal:      standard assign
   add (+):     The old assign will not be deleted but expanded by the selected
                directory. So you can create multi-directory assigns.
                This is only possible if there exists at least one assign with
                the given name.
   path (P):    The logical device is assigned to the filename. For example an
                assign to df0: is connected to the new disk after a disk
                change.
   late (L):    The assignment is made only when something or somebody uses
                this device. So you can create a device without having mounted
                or inserted a volume.

   @{i}Add @{ui} gives you two choices
   temporary:       will create or expand the logical device if possible.
   to user-startup: will add a line to the file s:user-startup, so
                    the device is available each time you restart.

   @{b}Sort by@{ub}

   If you want to know which assigns are made to a specific volume or directory,
   choose @{i}Sort by Path @{ui}, and the list will be resorted.
   You can always return to the name based order by choosing
   @{i}Sort by Name @{ui}.

   @{b}Reload@{ub}

   If other programs change assigns, MainPrefs will not update the list until
   you click on @{i}Reload @{ui}.
   When MainPrefs changes assigns, it will always update the list immediately.

   @{b}Remove@{ub}

   If an entry in the list is selected, clicking on the @{i}Remove @{ui}-Button
   will either delete the assign ("temporary") or remove it from the file
   user-startup ("from user-startup").
   If it is part of a multi-directory assign, only the selected entry will be
   deleted (of course the directory is not deleted from disk!).


  @{b}Notes@{ub}

  When you create an assign that has not the type "add" the current assign is
  removed. So you can change the type of an assign by clicking on it, changing
  the assign type and then choosing @{i}Add @{ui}.
  When you click on an assign, specify the type @{i}add @{ui} and then click
  @{i}Add @{ui}, then you will find the same assign twice in the list. This is
  possible with AmigaOS although it is senseless. Don't be confused.

  To create boot-resistent assigns, you have to add a new line to the file
  @{" s:user-startup " link prog} which is executed each time the Amiga is
  booting (e.g. "assign fonts: pagestream:fonts add").

  @{i}Remove->from user-startup @{ui} doesn't find all assigns in
  s:user-startup because of different paths like S: or sys:s. If this happens
  you have to change the file by hand.

  If other programs change assigns while MainPrefs is running, MainPrefs will
  show the changes as soon as you use @{i}Reload @{ui}.

@endnode

@node variables "Variables"

  @{b}Variables@{ub}

  The ENV directory contains all global environment variables. Some
  preferences are only changeable by changing these variables.
  Clicking on directories (which have the value <DIR>), including the parent
  directory "..", leads to the most available variables and lets you change
  them, multiline variables can be edited separately.
  The @{" order of the list and the handling of non-ASCII files " link config}
  can be changed. New variables can be created and old ones be deleted.

  Click on a variable. If the variable consists of one line, its value
  appears beneath the list and can be edited by keyboard. Press <RETURN> to
  end editing. The value will be changed immediately.
  If the variable consists of several lines, the value gadget is diasabled.
  Double-click on the entry or click on @{i}Edit @{ui} to open the specified
  @{" editor " link editor}.
  You can also start the editor with one line variables using the same
  procedure.

   @{b}Edit @{ub}

   Pressing this button will invoke the @{" editor " link editor}. When you have
   edited the variable and returned to MainPrefs, the value will be adjusted.

   @{b}Add @{ub}

   After a click on this button you will be asked for the variables name
   (independent of the currently shown directory).
   Click on Ok when you have entered the name, and the new variable will
   be created (temporary, in ENV:) without any value. You can also specify
   subdirectories.
   Change the variable and save it if necessary.

   @{b}Delete @{ub}

   Click on this button to delete the chosen variable. It will be deleted
   in ENV: and ENVARC:.
   CAUTION! The variable will be lost irrecoverably!

   @{b}Save @{ub}

   By pressing <RETURN>, the variable will have the entered value until the
   next time you start the Amiga. Clicking @{i}Save @{ui} will make the value
   the standard for this variable that will be assigned to the variable after
   each boot procedure (the old value is destroyed!).

   @{b}Reload @{ub}

   If other programs change variables, this button allows to read the
   variables again. MainPrefs shows its changes always immediately.

   @{b}Preset @{ub}

   With this button you can change the value to the standard value for this
   variable (the contents saved in the directory ENVARC:).
   If the variable consist of several lines or @{" non-ASCII text " link config}, there will be
   no visible effect as the contents are not shown. You have to @{i}Edit @{ui}
   this variable to see the changes.


  @{b}Notes@{ub}
  You should be cautious when editing or deleting variables in ENV:,
  especially the @{" non-ASCII files " link config}.

  Changing or deleting important environment variables may lead to
  unpredictable results!

@endnode

@node config "Settings"

  @{b}Settings@{ub}

  On this page you can configure MainPrefs.


   @{b}Editor@{ub}

   You can @{" change the standard editor " link editor} by clicking on the
   file request gadget or by droppig the editors icon into the window.

   @{b}Save changes at exit@{ub}

   When this option is selected, MainPrefs @{" saves the settings " link prefs}
   when you @{" quit the program " link quit}. If it is not selected
   and you want to quit, MainPrefs will only remind you of your changes.

   @{b}Show variable drawers first@{ub}

   The order of the entries in the variable list can be specified.
   If selected, directories are positioned at the head of the list,
   otherwise all entries are ordered alphabetically.

   @{b}Show only ASCII variables@{ub}

   The ENV: directory contains also files that do not consist of editable
   text. MainPrefs defines files that have at least one unprintable
   character in the first 256 bytes as non-ASCII file.
   If this button is selected, MainPrefs hides these and shows
   only editable files.
   Otherwise the whole directory is shown. Non-ASCII files can also be edited
   if you specify a suitable @{" editor " link editor}. Anyway you should
   know what you are doing!


  @{b}Save@{ub}

  With this button you can @{" saves the settings " link prefs}.

@endnode

@node help "Help"

  @{b}Help@{ub}

  You can always get help by pressing the @{i}help @{ui} key. The current topic
  will be shown.
  MenuHelp is available, so when the mouse is over a menu item and you press
  @{i}help @{ui}, you will get help for this item.

  Choosing the menu entry always opens the first page of the manual.

  Should a question stay unanswered, contact the @{" MainPrefs Team " link team}.


  see also
  @{" Support address " link team}
@endnode

@node editor "Editor"

  @{b}Change Editor@{ub}

  You can specify the editor used to edit the files of type "Edit" in the
  @{" system " link prog} list and the @{" variables " link variables}.
  The standard editor is @{i}c:ed @{ui}.

  The chosen editor will be invoked as CLI command each time you edit a
  file or variable, given the actual name as argument.

  If you want to keep this editor as standard, you have to @{" save the preferences " link prefs}
  on the @{" settings page " link config}.


  see also
  @{" Save preferences " link prefs}
  @{" System           " link prog}
  @{" Variables        " link variables}
  @{" Settings         " link config}
@endnode

@node prefs "Preferences"

  @{b}Save preferences@{ub}

  MainPrefs saves in its preference file the actual @{" system " link prog}
  list and the specified @{" settings " link config}.

  The preference file is called @{i}MainPrefs.prefs @{ui} and should be in the
  MainPrefs directory or in the place given by the @{" tooltypes " link use}.
  The next time you start the program these preferences are immediately
  available.

  The assigns and environment variables are @{b}not@{ub} saved.

  You can delete the preferences simply by deleting the file @{i}MainPrefs.prefs @{ui}.

  Preference files from older versions of MainPrefs will be loaded, converted
  and immediately saved in the new format when you start the program.

@endnode

@node info "About"

  @{b}About@{ub}

  The current version and the date of the last change will appear.

  Use this information when sending a bug report.


  see also
  @{" MainPrefs Team " link team}

@endnode

@node iconify "Iconify"

  @{b}Iconify@{ub}

  MainPrefs can be iconified. It will close its window and stay as icon on the
  workbench. Double-click on its icon or select the icon and choose "Open" in
  the workbench menu to open the window again.

  Remember that changes of @{" assigns " link assigns} and @{" variables " link variables}
  are not shown until you reload each list.

@endnode

@node quit "Quit"

  @{b}Quit@{ub}

  As alternative to clicking the windows close gadget the menu item allows
  leaving the program.

  If you have not selected @{i}Save changes at exit @{ui} a requester bewares you
  of too hasty actions if you have changed the @{" system " link prog} list or
  one of the the other @{" settings " link config}.

@endnode

@node errors "Problems"

  @{b}Problems@{ub}

  Version 2.0x contained several bugs because the testing phase was too short.
  With the current @{" MainPrefs Team " link team} version 2.1 could be tested
  intensively, many features were added and many errors removed.

  Are there still any problems?

  Then contact the @{" MainPrefs Team " link team}, and we will do our best to
  solve your problem.


  see also
  @{" Support " link team}
@endnode

@node todo "What is missing"

  @{b}What is missing:@{ub}

  - other catalogs

  Every other proposal is welcome.

  If you are looking for a list of changes since the last version, please read
  the file @{i}mainprefs.readme @{ui} in the MainPrefs directory.

  see also
  @{" Support " link team}
@endnode

